******
[3] United Kingdom, Devon, imported
Date: 30 Aug 2008
Source: Press and Journal [edited]
<http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/813327?UserKey=0>


Farming ministry DEFRA last night [29 Aug 2008] urged farmers to think
about where they are sourcing animals, after it confirmed 8 cattle imported
from Germany to a farm in Devon were infected with the deadly bluetongue
virus. It is the 3rd time this week that the disease has been found in
animals brought in from the continent. On Wed 27 Aug 2008, Defra said
bluetongue was discovered in rams imported from a disease zone in France to
Lewes in East Sussex and Hemel Hempstead in Hertfordshire.

DEFRA said the latest case involved a batch of 20 bulling heifers imported
from a disease zone in Germany more than a week ago to Tiverton. In all
cases, the virus was picked up through post-import testing. DEFRA said
there was still no evidence the disease, which is spread between animals by
midges, was circulating in the midge population in the areas in England
where it had been found.

But the National Beef Association feared bluetongue could be lurking
undiscovered in England and urged farmers to vaccinate their stock.
Vice-chairman Frank Momber said: "These animals (imported to Devon) were
sourced from an area in Germany which has still to report circulating BTV8
(the strain of bluetongue) virus in 2008."

Scientists in the UK are increasingly certain that bluetongue is already
moving inside Britain too. "If importers must bring in stock, they should
not accept word-of-mouth affirmation from suppliers that the animals carry
no bluetongue risk and protect their reputations and their own cattle by
insisting on a vaccination certificate that has been signed by a vet."

Mr Momber said that, with bluetongue having been confirmed in Britain last
September 2007, there was no room for complacency. He urged farmers in the
English Protection to redouble vaccination efforts to prevent the virus
from spreading.

The ministry also last night [29 Aug 2008] confirmed the extension of the
bluetongue protection zone into Cumbria and Northumberland from 12.01 AM on
Monday [1 Sep 2008]. The decision essentially closes the border to all
sheep, goat and cattle movements from England into Scotland, except for
animals that are vaccinated and which have gained immunity. These animals
also have be accompanied by veterinary certification that the vaccine was
administered by a vet. Movements of animals from the disease free zone in
Scotland into England are not affected.

